<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Head Praises Beijing's `Important Role' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603083894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0619 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, March 15 (XINHUA) -- U.N. 
Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali today praised China, a 
permanent member of the U.N. Security Council, for playing a 
more and more important role in the world organization and 
international affairs. 
  The U.N. chief was speaking to Chinese Deputy Foreign 
Minister Liu Huaqiu when they met here today. 
  Butrus-Ghali said the U.N. and China have cooperated very 
well on U.N. affairs and important international issues. 
  Under the current situation, the secretary-general said, it 
is quite necessary to encourage developing countries to take 
part in U.N. affairs since they form the bulk of the world body 
consisting of more than 180 member nations. 
  To encourage all developing countries to play a positive 
role 
in international problems is also significant to maintaining 
world peace and promoting economic development, said 
Butrus-Ghali. 
  He said the U.N. needs close cooperation from developing 
countries since they can express their wishes and requests 
through the world body. 
  Only by doing so, can the U.N. truly stand for their 
interests, he said. 
  Referring to the World Women's Congress to be held in 
Beijing 
in September 1995, Butrus-Ghali said that it will be a prominent 
meeting in the world. 
  He praised China for making outstanding preparations for the 
congress. 
  The U.N. chief also said that the congress will exert 
far-reaching influence on the promotion of women's status in the 
world. 
  Butrus-Ghali said he will visit China this year together 
with 
U.N. officials in charge of the World Women's Congress to help 
prepare for the congress, he said. 
  The Chinese deputy foreign minister agreed to Butrus-Ghali's 
views on the role of developing countries, saying that they will 
play a more and more important role in international affairs. 
  Liu emphasized that the Chinese Government attaches great 
importance to the World Women's Congress. 
  He said the Chinese Government will make proper preparations 
as the U.N. requires. 
  Liu arrived in Argentina on Sunday [13 March] on a visit at 
the invitation of the Argentine Foreign Ministry. 

</TEXT>

