<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Calls on U.S. to Meet `Agreed' Commitments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503173794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1625 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 15 (XINHUA) -- The Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) stressed today that it had 
completely carried out its commitments as far as inspection of 
its nuclear sites was concerned and called on the United States 
to carry out those agreed by it. 
  A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry said that the DPRK had 
fully accepted nuclear inspections by the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) within the time limits set under an accord 
between the two sides. 
  He noted that the inspections were implemented on the basis 
of full discussions between IAEA inspectors and DPRK 
administrative personnel at the country's nuclear facilities. 
  He also said all the problems emerging during the 
inspections 
have been solved satisfactorily under the IAEA's requirements, 
which has been recognized by the authority. 
  The spokesman added that during inter-Korean working-level 
contacts aimed at realizing an exchange of special envoys, the 
DPRK unilaterally took a resolute and magnanimous attitude so as 
to pave the way for that procedure. 
  However, he said, the United States had failed to carry out 
its own commitments. "The U.S. introduced two additional 
prerequisites when announcing the suspension of joint military 
exercises" added the spokesman. 
  They were that the nuclear inspections by IAEA must be 
implemented satisfactorily and exchanges of North-South Korean 
envoys be realized. 
  "The United States still insists on these two prerequisites 
and it is by no means justifiable" the spokesman said. 
  He reiterated that if the United States did not carry out 
its 
own agreed commitments, the DPRK would regard it as a break-down 
of communications and would take appropriate measures, including 
suspending inter-Korean working-level contacts and refusing to 
attend the third-round of U.S.-DPRK meetings scheduled for 
Geneva. 

</TEXT>

