<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Boeing Company Supports MFN Status </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603084194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0540 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603084194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 15 (XINHUA) -- The U.S. Boeing 
Company said here today it fully supports the continuation of 
most favored nation (MFN) trading status for China. 
  Lawrence Clarkson, vice president of Boeing, made these 
remarks at a symposium on U.S.-China relations held by the 
Council on Foreign Relations. 
  Clarkson said that "the American people would be better 
served if the divisive annual debate on MFN was avoided." 
  "Bilateral issues between our countries should be addressed 
as they would be normally between two countries who share 
significant mutual interests," he noted. 
  China is now the United States' 8th largest trading partner, 
and U.S. exports to China grew 17.36 percent in 1993 to 8.7 
billion U.S. dollars. 
  "U.S. exports to China in 1993 supported more than 167,000 
U.S. jobs," Clarkson said. "China trade also creates thousands 
of jobs for U.S. retailers, wholesalers, and importers." 
  He also said that during the next 15 years, China will need 
800 commercial planes worth 40 billion dollars, making it the 
world's third largest aviation market. 
  "Boeing and McDonnell Douglas are currently well positioned 
in the Chinese market," he pointed out. "But Airbus, Fokker and 
the Russians are waiting to quickly take advantage if the 
relationship between the United States and China deteriorates." 
  Clarkson said the Boeing Company believes strongly that U.S. 
President Bill Clinton should extend MFN status for China and 
that Congress should support such a decision. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

