<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Group To Continue Hong Kong Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603034794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0327 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603034794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Foreign 
Minister Qian Qichen said that despite a breakdown in 
Sino-British talks on Hong Kong political issues, work in other 
fields that requires efforts from both sides has been underway 
and will continue. 
  Qian made the remark at a news conference here today. 
  "Sino-British talks on the arrangement of Hong Kong 1994/95 
elections have broken down," he said. "But this does not mean 
work of the Joint Liason Group will suspend." 
  Negotiations on the new Hong Kong airport are continuing, 
too, he said. 
  "In my view," Qian said, "both sides should make efforts to 
ensure Hong Kong's prosperity and stability. Despite a 
breakdown of Sino-British talks on the political structure 
arrangement of Hong Kong, China still cares about Hong Kong's 
economy and the livelihood of its people." 
  China will try its best to cooperate with the British side, 
he said. 
  "Whether or not cooperation can proceed smoothly depends on 
both the attitude and action of the British side," he said. 

</TEXT>

