<H3> <TI>   Urges Patient Talks on DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603050394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0446 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603050394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA) -- China hopes that the 
situation on the Korean peninsula will move towards relaxation 
and stability and also hopes the peninsula be nuclear free, 
Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today. 
  "This conforms to China's interests as well as to the 
regional and world interests," Qian said at a press conference 
this morning. 
  Asked about the International Atomic Energy Agency's 
difficulties in inspection of nuclear facilities in the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), Qian said China 
supports DPRK to hold negotiations with the United States, the 
Republic of Korea, and the International Atomic Energy Agency. 
  In the past the negotiations met some setbacks and achieved 
some progresses too, Qian said. 
  Now some difficulties have cropped up again. "We believe 
that 
so long as all sides are patient in negotiations and do not 
adopt measures to make the situation complicated, the 
negotiations will achieve important progress," he said. 

</TEXT>

