<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   CPPCC Committee Urges Party-to-Party Contact Across Straits </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603100494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0917 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603100494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA) -- The Revolutionary 
Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang (RCCK) today called on the 
Taiwan authorities to agree to formal contacts between the 
Communist Party of China (CPC) and the Kuomintang in Taiwan. 
  RCCK Vice Chairman Li Ganliu made the call on behalf of his 
party at Wednesday's [16 March] meeting of the National 
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative 
Conference (CPPCC). 
  "The Taiwan authorities should abandon illusions, face the 
reality, accept CPC's proposals on opening talks between the two 
parties and establishing direct exchanges of mail, trade, and 
shipping and air services between the two sides of the Taiwan 
straits, and make decisions that will benefit the Chinese 
nation," he said. 
  Relations across the Straits and the situation relating to 
the peaceful reunification of China have undergone significant 
changes in the past year, and the major trend of changes is 
positive, he said. 
  Li reviewed development of relations between the two sides: 
economic links between the two sides are growing, with Taiwan 
investment in the mainland increasing by a big margin; trade and 
personnel exchanges between the two sides are expanding rapidly; 
and agreements reached between the two non-governmental 
organizations, namely the Strait Exchange Foundation of Taiwan 
and the Association of Relations Across the Taiwan Straits of 
the mainland, marked a historical step forward in relations 
between the two sides. 
  He pointed out, however, that the Taiwan authorities 
stubbornly cling to their policy of blocking direct commercial 
and communication links with the mainland. On the other hand, 
they are pursuing a splittist policy of "two Chinas" on the 
international scene by carrying out "money campaigns" and 
"flexible diplomacy." Last year, they stepped up activities for 
Taiwan's "return to the United Nations" in an attempt to gain 
"dual recognition." After the attempt was thwarted, they have 
resorted to "holiday-making diplomacy" recently. 
  Facts have shown that there has not been a fundamental 
change 
in the Taiwan authorities' wrong stand on the reunification of 
China. Their activities are in contradiction with their 
repeatedly proclaimed stand of "one China." 
  He said the reunification of China is an irresistible trend 
of the times and the aspirations of people on both sides of the 
straits. Any attempts to delay the cause of reunification and 
to create "two Chinas" are doomed to fail, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3023 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi051_k_94024" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

