<F P=100> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economist Offers Advice to CPPCC on Banking Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603084294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0720 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 16 (XINHUA) -- The central 
government must not relax its macro-controls over the country's 
banking industry after banks enjoy full operational autonomy, 
according to a well-known Chinese economist. 
  "Macro-controls over the banking sector, however, should be 
distinguished from government mandates to banks," said Wang 
Chuanlun, a member of the National Committee of the Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) and an 
economics professor of Chinese People's University. 
  To have macro-control means, the professor said, the 
government must establish and improve various kinds of financial 
markets in a systematic way. 
  First to be established, Wang said, is a market for 
short-term inter-banking lending and borrowing, to be followed 
successively by a bill discount market, a market for the trading 
of treasury bonds, a market for the trading of enterprise bonds 
and shares and a mortgage loan market. 
  In the meantime, he said, the existing foreign exchange 
market should be improved. 
  For the central bank, he said, the main function is to 
maintain the value of the Chinese yuan and determine its 
exchange rates with other currencies. 
  In converting existing banks into purely commercial banks, 
he 
said, the first thing to do is to determine their assets through 
careful auditing. 
  It is necessary, he said, for the government to decide 
establishing some "policy" banks. But the government should 
have concrete decisions on who exercise control over such banks, 
where their founding capital should come from, and who will bear 
their future risks and losses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

