<F P=100> Military </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aircraft Maintenance Crews Use High Technology </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803120894 Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1400 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0803120894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1400 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Mandarin </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video from the "Night News" </F>
program] 
  [Text] The Air Force's aircraft maintenance troops 
extensively apply new and high technology, thus markedly 
improving their aircraft maintenance and support ability. [video 
shows pan shot of the interior of a garage where soldiers are 
seen working on machinery, then cuts to show five technicians in 
white coats servicing some instruments] 
  Using computer software and modern (?earthquake-sounding) 
technology, aircraft maintenance troops have developed simulated 
training and instructional systems complete with images, texts, 
and sounds. To train maintenance crews in simulated 
maintenance, assembly, disassembly, and debugging services, and 
to cultivate high-level aircraft maintenance personnel, they 
have established an aircraft maintenance management network 
whose scope ranges from various large Air Force units to 
divisions and regiments. This has effectively improved the 
accuracy and timeliness of equipment maintenance. [video shows 
close-up shots of a computer keyboard, a diagram on a computer 
screen, and a pantograph moving across a sheet of white paper, 
then cuts to show men in military uniforms welding parts 
together and technicians in white coats adjusting instruments] 

</TEXT>

