<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Major Liberalization of Trade To Begin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1303071394 Beijing CHINA DAILY (BUSINESS WEEKLY) in 
English 13-19 Mar 94 pp 1, 2 </F>

<F P=103> HK1303071394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY (BUSINESS WEEKLY) </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Wang Yong: "Major Steps To Liberalize Trade Are </F>
Imminent"] 
  [Text] China this week will announce major steps to 
liberalize its trade to help pave the way for its return to 
GATT, the world trade body, said a senior government official. 
  China will ensure "maximum possible flexibility on tariff 
and 
non-tariff measures as well as other issues of interest to GATT 
parties, while maintaining a balance of rights and obligations 
in GATT," said the official, Long Yongtu. 
  Long is in charge of GATT affairs for the Ministry of 
Foreign 
Trade and Economic Cooperation (Moftec). 
  Long made the remarks in an interview with BUSINESS WEEKLY 
on 
the eve of the 16th session of the GATT Working Party on China, 
to be held from March 15-18 in Geneva. 
  Long, who is general secretary of the Chinese delegation, 
which left for Geneva on Saturday, said details of the 
"significant measures" would be announced then. 
  "Some of the measures will be bound to specific 
implementation timetables," Long said. 
  "And," he added, "we will make new commitments to foreign 
exchange reforms." 
  These impending measures should better position China for 
resuming contracting party status in the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade (GATT), economists said. 
  The United States and the European Union (EU) have 
complained 
that China's proposed concessions to the Uruguay Round of GATT 
trade negotiations are not enough. 
  But the U.S. and EU agree that China could be allowed a 
transitional period to revise its proposals after it rejoins 
GATT. Analysts said the new measures by China on liberalizing 
trade can be significant steps in that direction. 
  Long's delegation to Geneva, which is led by Moftec 
Vice-Minister Gu Yongjiang, is the largest of any sent by China 
to Geneva. 
  Yu Xiaosong, Vice-Minister of the State Economic and Trade 
Commission which masterminds the nation's industrial policies, 
is vice-chairman of the mission. 
  Long pointed out that the Geneva session on China's re-entry 
into GATT is the first following the conclusion of the Uruguay 
Round of trade talks. 
  "It is high time for China to rejoin GATT," Long said. 
  His opinion is based on three reasons. 
  Firstly, China's economic reforms in the past 15 years, 
particularly those adopted this year, have substantially pushed 
the country's economy onto a market-based track. 
  "Even the U.S. and EU have acknowledged the remarkable 
progress China has made," Long said. 
  U.S. Assistant Trade Representative Dorothy Dwoskin and EU 
Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan visited China last month and 
gained an appreciation of China's economic reforms. 
  Secondly, China has accepted the notion of a transitional 
period for it to meet GATT's requirements. 
  Thirdly, China's resumption of its GATT status would be the 
prerequisite for becoming a founding member of the World Trade 
Organization (WTO), which is to replace GATT next year as the 
primary international free-trade body. 
  "Without the participation of China as a founding member, 
WTO 
will be incomplete and its universality will be weakened," Long 
said. 
  If China, the world's 11th largest trading nation, should be 
kept outside WTO it would be a setback for the international 
trade system, he added. 
  Long reaffirmed that China would not seek to reduce its 
obligations for maintaining world trade once it rejoins Gatt. 
  "We will not dilute our commitment to GATT or the WTO by 
resorting to treatment as a developing nation," he said. 
  GATT rules, as well as preliminary regulations drawn up by 
the WTO, stipulate different treatment for developing and 
developed nations on certain issues. "We are only insisting on 
being treated as a developing nation when there are different 
stipulations for the two categories," he explained. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3056 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi051_n_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-051 </AU>
